Nick Clover says the moon is made of cheese, but it's actually made of Font Converter

> Does anyone know how I can get gadtools gadgets to use a font generated
> with Font Converter? I've got a few WB utilities that I'd like to use an

Of course, you can hackyhackyhackhack the font into a Blitz font object.
Something along the lines of:

; Stick this in after you create the font as in the example.

*if.intuifont = Addr IntuiFont(0)
fn$ = "thinpaz8.font"
*if\_fontname = &fn$
*if\_ysize = 8
*if\_font = *thinpaz8Font

Use IntuiFont 0
GTButton ....

; Remember to clear all these fields manually (just set them to 0), so
; Blitz doesn't try to free them

Oh, and in the example code, where Ott sets the value of the font name to
something in the pointer - don't do that, assign a new string and use the
address of that (like the above). Otherwise it'll just be put into temporary string space
and overwritten later.

Actually, that might not work, I think gadtools.library just takes the
pointer to the font name and size and tries to open the font from
disk/memory. Right, what you might want to do, after hacking it into the
IntuiFont is call:

AddFont_(*thinpaz8Font)

and hope that gadtools.library tries to get the font from memory before
disk.

Once you're finished using the font (completely! - freed gadlists and
things) and perhaps before you clear the IntuiFont structure, but that
might not matter:

RemFont(*thinpaz8Font)

> internal font as a fall back if the user requested font cannot be found
> (and to help keep the FONTS: drawer a bit smaller, I hate having to have

Just load the font from your own directory, it's perfectly legal to
specify the full path to the font. The disadvantage of this (and including
it in your code actually) is that the fallback font will not be displayed
in the font requester. However, if you have it as a file on disk, you can
"assign add" the fonts: directory to your one so that your font will also
appear in the requester. I don't think you can do this at all if it is in
your code.

