@NODE "Mail_11" " Re: Getting a Shape "
From: David McMinn <mcminn@redhotant.com>
Date: 01-06-01 16:12:35
Subject: @{b}Re: Getting a Shape@{ub}

Paul Bray says the moon is made of cheese, but it's actually made of Getting a Shape

>    How do you get a shape from an interleaved bitmap?
>    GetaShape says it won't work with interleaved bitmaps
>    like my Workbench.

To do it properly, you'd want to write a function which reads from the
interleaved bitmap and then writes to the shape bitmap.

But to save myself some brain effort, you could try something like this:

; this constant defines a bitmap which is free to be overwritten
; when you are grabbing the shape
#DUMMYBITMAP = 1
Statement ILGetaShape{shp.w, x.w, y.w, w.w, h.w}
    curbmp.w = Used BitMap
    InitShape shp,w,h,Depth(curbmp)
    ShapesBitMap 0,#DUMMYBITMAP

    BltBitMap_ Addr BitMap(curbmp),x,y,Addr BitMap(#DUMMYBITMAP),0,0,w,h,$C0,-1,0
    Use BitMap curbmp
End Statement

WbToScreen 0
ScreensBitMap 0,0
Use BitMap 0 ; the interleaved bitmap

ILGetaShape{0, 0, 0, 32, 32}

; whatever

This probably will not work if your workbench is more than 256 colours
(i.e. on a GFX card and using a high depth).

